3.1 Solar Wind

Author
Affiliation

Alexander Smolka

Technical University of Munich
Lunar and Planetary Exploration

Published

January 7, 2024

Origin

Parker Spirals of the Sun because of the solar rotation (Bittencourt, 2004).

The rotation axis of the Sun is inclined by \(7.25\,\mathrm{\degree}\) with respect to the ecliptic plane (Russell, 2013).

\(400\,\mathrm{km/s}\) (Russell, 2013)

\(\left(400 - 500\right)\,\mathrm{km/s}\) nominal speed (Bennett et al., 2013; Farrell et al., 2015)

Drift velocity of electrons: \(300\,\mathrm{km/s}\) (Bittencourt, 2004)

Mariner 2 measurements of the velocity at the near-Earth rotation: \(\left(400 - 700\right)\,\mathrm{km/s}\) based on a roughly \(27\,\mathrm{d}\) cycle (Neugebauer & Snyder, 1966).

Composition

The solar wind is a magnetized and highly conducting plasma consisting of electrons, protons, and heavier ions. At Earth’s distance to the Sun, its nominal density is about \(5\,\mathrm{cm^{\mathrm{-3}}}\) electrons and ions (Russell, 2013). For the Moon, this density can vary greatly based on transient events like CME or the Moon’s passage through Earth’s magnetotail.

With the solar wind propagating in all directions, the density decreases inversely proportional to the square of the distance from the Sun.

Protons and Electrons

About \(96\,\mathrm{\%}\) of all ions are protons (Futaana et al., 2012).

Proton density of the solar wind measured by Mariner 2 varied between \(\left(1 - 50\right)\,\mathrm{cm^{\mathrm{-3}}}\), with an average daily average of \(5\,\mathrm{cm^{\mathrm{-3}}}\) protons (Neugebauer & Snyder, 1966).

Ions and Heavier Elements

The majority of the remaining ions are alpha particles, i.e., helium nuclei \(\ce{He++}\), making up about \(4\,\mathrm{\%}\) of the solar wind ion particles (Futaana et al., 2012).

Interplanetary Magnetic Field

The solar wind exerts a magnetic field, called the Interplanetary Magnetic Field (IMF), of roughly \(5\,\mathrm{nT}\) in the ecliptic plane at \(1\,\mathrm{AU}\), though its orientation is highly variable (Russell, 2013). Zhao & Hoeksema (1995) reported that in situ observations round that the horizontal component of the IMF, while being generally less than \(5\,\mathrm{nT}\) in strength, “jumps from one finite value to another with opposite polarity”.

  • Figure
  • Downloads

Due to its high conductivity, the solar wind’s magnetic field tends to be relatively frozen inside the streaming plasma (Bittencourt, 2004).

Interaction with the Lunar Surface

Distribution

Assuming that the particles in the solar wind are spatially evenly distributed, the particle distribution on the planetary surface is only a function of the solar zenith angle \(\psi_s\). This angle can be derived in terms of the sub-solar longitude \(\Theta_s\) and latitude \(\Phi_s\) by \(\cos\psi_s = \cos\Theta_s \cdot \cos\Phi_s\).

Let \(\left(\Theta_s, \Phi_s\right)\) be a spherical sub-solar surface coordinate with \(r\) equal to the central body’s radius. For positive solar zenith angles, the PDF of the solar wind particle distribution on the surface is \[\begin{equation} f(\Theta_s, \Phi_s) d\Theta d\Phi= \frac{1}{4} \cos\psi_s d\Theta d\Phi= \frac{1}{4} \cos\Theta_s \cos\Phi_s d\Theta d\Phi, \label{eq:solar_wind_position_pdf} \end{equation}\] which can be integrated over the angular arguments of the dayside hemisphere, which is \(-\pi / 2 \leq \Theta_s \leq \pi / 2\) and \(-\pi / 2 \leq \Phi_s \leq \pi / 2\), to yield the CDF \[\begin{equation} F(\Theta_s, \Phi_s) = \int_{-\pi/2}^{\Phi_s} \int_{-\pi/2}^{\Theta_s} \frac{1}{4} \cos\Theta\cos\Phi d\Theta d\Phi= \frac{1}{4} \left(1 - \sin\Theta_s\right) \left(1 - \sin\Phi_s\right). \label{eq:solar_wind_position_cdf} \end{equation}\] The two arguments can easily be separated into two individual CDFs, one for each angular position: \[\begin{align} F(\Theta_s) &= \frac{1}{2} \left(1 - \sin\Theta_s\right) \\ F(\Phi_s) &= \frac{1}{2} \left(1 - \sin\Phi_s\right). \end{align}\]

For the numerical sampling of this distribution, let \(R_u\in \left[0, 1\right]\) be a uniformly distributed random variable with realization \(r_u\) of \(R_u\sim f(r_u) = 1\). The CDFs can be set equal to such realization and through the inversion technique, a numerical function for the sampling of the surface coordinates can be found. \[\begin{align} r_u&= F(\Theta_s) = \frac{1}{2} \left(1 - \sin\Theta_s\right) \quad\Rightarrow\quad \Theta_s = \sin^{-1}\left(1 - 2 r_u\right) \\ r_u&= F(\Phi_s) = \frac{1}{2} \left(1 - \sin\Phi_s\right) \quad\Rightarrow\quad \Phi_s = \sin^{-1}\left(1 - 2 r_u\right). \end{align}\]

using .ExESS
using CairoMakie, GeoMakie, ColorSchemes

#::. main plotting function
function plot_surface_distribution()

    # define grid (leave gaps for better GeoMakie usage)
    lng, lat = deg2rad.(-179:1:179), deg2rad.(-89:1:89)

    # calculate solar wind distribution probability
    p = [pos_pdf(SolarWindSurfaceDistribution(LUNAR_RADIUS), lng[i], lat[j]) 
            for i in eachindex(lng), j in eachindex(lat)]

    # create figure and axis
    fig = Figure(;resolution=(600,300))
    ax = GeoAxis(fig[1,1]; 
        bottomspinevisible  = false,
        dest                = "+proj=natearth", 
        leftspinevisible    = false,
        rightspinevisible   = false,
        topspinevisible     = false,
        xgridcolor          = (:black, 0.3),
        xlabel              = "Local Time, LT [h]",
        xtickformat         = Makie.automatic,
        xticklabelpad       = 1.0,
        xticks              = ([-180,-90,0,90,180], ["0","6","12","18","24"]),
        ylabel              = "Sub-Solar Latitude, Φₛ [°]",
        ytickformat         = Makie.automatic,
    )
    
    # plot probability heatmap
    hm = heatmap!(ax, rad2deg.(lng), rad2deg.(lat), p .* 100; #
        colormap=ColorSchemes.lipari, 
        colorrange=(0,25))

    # add colorbar
    Colorbar(fig[:,2], hm; 
        ticklabelpad=.5, 
        label="Probability [%]")

    # save figure in different formats
    save(joinpath(@__DIR__,"surface_distribution.pdf"), fig)
    save(joinpath(@__DIR__,"surface_distribution.png"), fig, px_per_unit=4)
end

Figure 1: Hourly averaged radial interplanetary magnetic field component of the heliospheric current sheet during ten “quiet” Sun condition intervals, to reflect an ambient IMF. Small dots show hourly averages, circles show daily averages with no values for days with fewer than 12 hourly samples. Copied from Zhao & Hoeksema (1995). Figure 2: Visualization of the solar wind distribution probability on a planetary surface in sub-solar coordinates. The peak of the PDF is obviously positioned at the sub-solar point and decreases with an increasing solar zenith angle. The night side can not be reached by any solar wind particles, thus, all probabilities with sub-solar longitudes \(\left| \Theta_s \right| > 90\,\mathrm{\degree}\) are zero.
